Here's a PlantUML sequence diagram representing the control flow of the incremental data migration tool:

```plantuml
@startuml duanfuxiang0_MysqlMigrationTool

participant "Main" as main
participant "Canal" as canal
participant "RowEventHandler" as handler
participant "BinlogParser" as parser
participant "DataModels" as models
participant "TargetDatabase" as target

main -> canal : Initialize
main -> handler : Create
main -> canal : RegisterEventHandler(handler)
main -> canal : Start()

loop For each binlog event
    canal -> handler : OnRow(e canal.RowsEvent)
    activate handler
    
    handler -> parser : Parse(e)
    activate parser
    
    parser -> models : Reflect and map data
    parser --> handler : Parsed data
    deactivate parser
    
    alt Insert event
        handler -> models : InsertToNew()
        models -> target : Execute INSERT query
    else Update event
        handler -> models : UpdateToNew()
        models -> target : Execute UPDATE query
    else Delete event
        handler -> models : DeleteFromNew()
        models -> target : Execute DELETE query
    end
    
    handler --> canal : Return
    deactivate handler
end

main -> canal : Close()

@enduml
```

This sequence diagram illustrates the control flow of the incremental data migration tool, focusing on the runtime message flow between components. It shows how the main function initializes the Canal, registers the RowEventHandler, and starts the process. The loop represents the continuous processing of binlog events, where each event is parsed, mapped to data models, and then applied to the target database based on the event type (insert, update, or delete).